               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311020-28-person296">
                  WATKIN 
                  LLOYD
               <interp inst="t18311020-28-person296" type="surname" value="LLOYD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311020-28-person296" type="given" value="WATKIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311020-28-person296" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18311020-28-viclabel158" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311020-28-victim295 t18311020-28-viclabel158"></join>. On the 18th of October, about eleven o'clock at night, I was going home, perfectly sober, and met the prisoner at the lower end of <placeName id="t18311020-28-crimeloc159">Bishopsgate-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18311020-28-crimeloc159" type="placeName" value="Bishopsgate-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18311020-28-crimeloc159" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311020-28-off156 t18311020-28-crimeloc159"></join> - she came against me, laid hold of my arm, and asked where I was going; I said home - she asked me to walk with her; I said No, and just at that time I felt my watch going out of my fob - I felt, and is was gone; I caught hold of her, and said she had my watch - she denied it; I called a watchman, who came instantly, and she immediately popped it into my waistcoat pocket - she had taken it from my fob; I did not know her before, and had given her no encouragement.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311020-28-person297">
                  ROBERT 
                  DIXON
               <interp inst="t18311020-28-person297" type="surname" value="DIXON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311020-28-person297" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311020-28-person297" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I was passing Bishopsgate-street, and saw a young man, a comapanion of the prisoner's, peeping round the corner, and saw the prosecutor struggling with the prisoner; I could see part of the chain hanging down in her hand - as soon as the young man round the corner saw me he ran away; I ran up, secured the prisoner, and saw her put the watch into Lloyd's waistcoat pocket.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. The prosecutor was quite in liquor; my sister came to the watch-house, and saw him - he could hardly stand. Witness. He was perfectly sober.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I met him in Bishopsgate-street quite in liquor - I spoke to him, and we turned up Skinner-street; he asked where I lived, and said he would go home with me, but all in a moment he said, "Stop, I have lost my watch;" I said he had not lost it in my company - he said he had, and struck me, and it was I that called the watchman, who came up; I said he had charged me with robbery - he felt, and said his watch was in his pocket.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18311020-28-verdict160" type="verdictDescription">
